description: From Middle English corbel, from Old French corbel, from Late Latin corbellus, corvellus, diminutive of Latin corvus (“raven”).

entries.meaning: (architecture) A structural member jutting out of a wall to carry a superincumbent weight.

verbs.description: corbel (third-person singular simple present corbels, present participle corbelling or corbeling, simple past and past participle corbelled or corbeled)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To furnish with a corbel or corbels; to support by a corbel; to make in the form of a corbel.
